messages.content: You are tasked with creating a structured output from the provided user message.

Full path
- /consumer/{username}/notifications

All HTTP methods acceptable
- false

Methods accepted (based on annotations in the code)
- HEAD: false
- POST: false
- OPTIONS: false
- TRACE: false
- GET: false
- PUT: true
- DELETE: true
- PATCH: false

Explanation
- The ConsumerController class has no class-level @RequestMapping, so the full path is exactly the method-level value: "/consumer/{username}/notifications".
- Two methods in this controller map to that exact path:
  - deleteAllNotifications is annotated with @RequestMapping(value = "/consumer/{username}/notifications", method = RequestMethod.DELETE) — so DELETE is accepted.
  - readAllNotifications is annotated with @RequestMapping(value = "/consumer/{username}/notifications", method = RequestMethod.PUT) — so PUT is accepted.
- No other @RequestMapping for that path is present in the provided code, and no mapping allowing "all methods" is used. Per your instruction to base acceptability on the code (not framework defaults), only the explicitly declared HTTP methods (PUT and DELETE) are considered acceptable.
